Facts about friendships:

• A person can maintain approx. 150 active relationships at a single time.

• We spend approximately 60% of our social efforts around 15 people.

Psychologist Dr Mary Kempnich reveals more about ‘Dunbar’s number’.⬇️

#InternationalDayofFriendship #Oxford #OxfordUni #OxfordUniversity

node.title: How many friends is too many?

#TruePlanet #OxfordUni #Oxford #OxfordUniversity #Environment #GlobalWarming

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by The University of Oxford on August 09, 2021. May be an image of body of water and text that says ''This report shows that already there are a lot of impacts of anthropogenic climate change- climate change has affected many extreme climate events ın every region around the world. 'There are things that we can stop from getting worse by keeping to the targets, but there are lot of changes that are already here and we need to keep that in mind when thinking about policy.' ROAD GI8SER Friederike Otto, Associate Director of the Environmental Change Institute at the University of Oxford TRUE PLANET'.

Photo by The University of Oxford on August 09, 2021. May be an image of fire, outdoors and text that says ''The IPCC Sixth Assessment Report (AR6) states that it is unequivocal that human influence has warmed the atmosphere ocean and land, and that this warming will continue as we keep emitting greenhouse gases into the atmosphere. 'It is very hard to imagine any credible scientist doubting this. Indeed, if we do not halt our emissions soon, our future climate could well become some kind of hel on Earth.' TimPalmer, Royal Society Research Professor at the University of Oxford TRUE PLANET'.

Photo by The University of Oxford on August 09, 2021. May be an image of outdoors and text that says ''We need to act on both methane and carbon dioxide emissions: and an easy first step would be for the UNFCCC, and UK government, to adopt accounting rules that reflect how these gases actually affect global temperature. Great to see the IPCC WG1 report has acknowledged this opportunity.' Myles Allen is Professor of Geosystem Science and Director of the Oxford Net Zero initiative. TRUE PLANET'.

Photo by The University of Oxford on August 09, 2021. May be an image of body of water and text that says ''It remains true that nothing is more important than getting the net emissions to carbon dioxide to zero, and doing it as soon as possible. Carbon dioxide accumulates in the atmosphere, and causes essentially irreversible warming, so any delay in progress toward net zero carbon dioxide emissions commits us to living with additional warming for thousands of years.' Raymond T. Pierrehumbert, Halley Professor of Physics, University of Oxford TRUE PLANET'.

NEW RESEARCH: Data show the impact of #COVID19 on pregnant women. ⬇️ 

• 1 in 10 pregnant women admitted to hospital with symptoms need intensive care.

• Over 99% of pregnant women admitted to hospital with symptomatic COVID-19 are unvaccinated.

Marian Knight, Professor of Maternal and Child Population Health at the Nuffield Department of Population Health and chief investigator of the study, said, ‘It is extremely good news that so few vaccinated pregnant women have been admitted to hospital with COVID-19. However, it is very concerning that admissions of pregnant women to hospital with COVID-19 are increasing and that pregnant women appear to be more severely affected by the Delta variant of the disease.

I cannot emphasise more strongly how important it is for pregnant women to get vaccinated in order to protect both them and their baby. Until they are vaccinated, pregnant women must continue to be extremely attentive to social distancing measures including mask wearing, 2m distancing and meeting outdoors where possible.'

Read more ➡️ ox.ac.uk/news
